1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 ({Committing
the knight} 6... Nc6 {is fully playable and may easily transpose to the main
lines after} 7. f3 {, but the game can take an entirely original course by
means of} h5 {[%cal Gf8h6] A provocative idea to stop the g2-g4 advance, by
which Black is declaring readiness to play for long with his king in the
center.} 8. Bc4 $1 (8. Qd2 {is the most natural move, though a bit premature
in the view of} Nxd4 9. Qxd4 (9. Bxd4 Bh6 $5 {(Black's surprising point!)} 10.
Bb5+ Bd7 11. Qd3 (11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Qf2 O-O {is approximately equal}) 11...
Bc6 12. O-O O-O 13. Bxf6 exf6 14. Kh1 Qb6 15. a4 Qc5 $11 {I. Saric - R.
Rapport, Warsaw, 2021}) 9... Bg7 10. O-O-O (10. Bb5+ Kf8 $1 11. Qd3 (11. Qd2
Qa5 12. Be2 a6 13. Bd4 Be6 14. a3 Nd7 $11) 11... Be6 12. O-O-O Rc8 {[%csl Rb5]}
13. e5 Ne8 14. Bxe8 Kxe8 15. exd6 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Qxd6 17. Qxd6 exd6 18. Bxa7 (
18. Rxd6 Ke7 19. Rd3 b6 $11) 18... Kd7 19. Bd4 Rhe8 $11) 10... O-O {is now
reasonable, for White should retreat his queen -} 11. Qd2 Be6 12. Kb1 Rc8 13.
Ne2 {[%cal Ge2f4,Ge2d4]} ({here} 13. h3 $2 {is running into the typical
exchange sacrifice} Rxc3 $1 14. Qxc3 Nd5 15. Qd3 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Qa5 $40) 13...
b5 14. h3 (14. Nf4 Bc4) (14. Nd4 Bc4) 14... Bc4 15. g4 h4 $5 16. Bg5 $140 Qc7
17. Bxh4 Rfd8 $13 {[%cal Gd6d5]}) 8... Bd7 ({after} 8... Bg7 9. Qd2 {we can
conclude that White has successfully overcome Rapport's move order}) ({if
Black is insisting on that idea by} 8... Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bh6 {, then White will
be a tempo up compared to the game after} 10. O-O O-O {and now} 11. Qd3 $16 {
[%cal Ga1d1,Gf3f4] in one go}) 9. Qd2 Nxd4 ({the remark to 8....Bg7 is
absolutely valid for} 9... Bg7 10. O-O-O {as well:} Rc8 (10... Na5 {is well
countered with the clever} 11. Be2 $1 Rc8 12. Kb1 Nc4 $140 13. Bxc4 Rxc4 14.
Nde2 O-O 15. Bd4 Rc6 (15... b5 16. e5 $16) 16. h3 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4]}) (10...
O-O {is inviting} 11. h3 {[%cal Gg2g4] and the g2-g4 push will question the
early h7-h5}) 11. Nxc6 $5 (11. Bb3 Na5 12. Kb1) 11... bxc6 (11... Rxc6 12. Bb3
O-O 13. Rhe1 Qa5 14. Kb1 $16) ({in reply to} 11... Bxc6 {White should not shy
away from the principled} 12. Bxa7 O-O 13. Bd4 $16) 12. Rhe1 Qa5 13. Bd4 O-O
14. e5 $16) 10. Qxd4 $5 ({the insertion of Bf1-c4 and Bc8-d7 seems to favor
White in case of} 10. Bxd4 Bh6 11. Qd3 O-O 12. O-O $14 {[%cal Gf3f4,Ga1d1] ;
the first player will try to prove that in the text as well}) 10... Bg7 11.
O-O-O O-O 12. Qd3 {[%cal Ge3d4]} Qa5 13. Bb3 Bc6 (13... Rfc8 14. Kb1) ({
one evidence is revealed by} 13... b5 $2 14. e5 $1 dxe5 15. Qxg6 $18) 14. Kb1
Nd7 15. Qd2 (15. Bd4 Nc5 16. Qe2 $14) 15... Bxc3 $5 (15... Rfc8 $143 16. Bg5
Bxc3 $140 $2 17. bxc3 Re8 18. g4 $1 hxg4 19. h4 $1 $18) (15... Nc5 $6 16. Nd5
Qd8 17. Bh6 $16) 16. bxc3 Ba4 (16... Nc5 17. Rhg1 {[%cal Gg2g4]} Nxb3 18. axb3
