1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 O-O 8. Qd2
Nc6 {In this initial position of the classical Dragon, my recommendation is} 9.
O-O-O {Before delving into the most critical lines, let us first look at the
minor ones:} h5 $6 {Here is this attempt to discourage the g2-g4 thrust again.}
({In such situations, in which the opponents have castled differently, a sharp
mutual race is expected. Therefore, from here on, the value of each move grows
and, until Bf1 is on its initial square,} 9... Bd7 $6 {is less effective.} 10.
g4 {is the natural reply and now:} Rc8 (10... h5 11. gxh5 ({it makes sense to
open the g-file against the enemy king rather than} 11. g5 Ne8) ({maintaining
the tension with} 11. h3 $5 {also poses problems}) 11... Nxh5 12. Nxc6 (12. Rg1
$5) 12... Bxc6 (12... bxc6 13. Bc4 Kh7 14. Rhg1 Rb8 15. f4 $16 {[%cal Gf4f5]})
13. Rg1 $16) (10... Ne5 11. h4 $16 {and Black has hardly anything better than
to transpose to 10...Rc8}) (10... Nxd4 {does not look consistent, after} 11.
Bxd4 Qa5 12. h4 b5 {is the only way to justify the appearance of Bd7, but
White can easily stop this expansion by means of} 13. a3 Rab8 $140 $6 (13... b4
14. Na2 $1 $18 {is another point}) 14. g5 $1 Nh5 15. Nd5 Qxd2+ 16. Rxd2 $18)
