1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 {Black has just committed
himself to the Scheveningen structure, but now the g4-square is not under
control, so} 6. g4 $1 a6 ({A famous principle insists on meeting an early
flank aggression with a central counterblow, but} 6... d5 $6 {is not a proper
example, e.g.} 7. exd5 {and now} Nxd5 {is definitely the better way to
recapture, but Black is going to have difficulties with the mobilization of
his forces, as well as a permanent problem with the isolated d5-pawn after} (
7... exd5 $2 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Qe2+ Be7 (9... Qe7 10. g5 Qxe2+ 11. Bxe2 $18 {
[%csl Rd5][%cal Gc3d5]}) 10. Nf5 $18) 8. Bb5+ Bd7 (8... Nd7 9. Nxd5 exd5 10.
Qe2+ $1 Qe7 11. Be3 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Qe2+ $1 {, forcing
the opponent to the awkward} Qe7 ({alas, after} 10... Be7 11. Nf5 {is once
again unpleasant to meet}) 11. Be3 {with much more harmonious development.}) (
6... Be7 7. g5 Nfd7 8. h4 {will transpose later to 6...a6 or 6...Nc6.}) (6...
Nc6 7. g5 Nd7 8. Be3 (8. h4 Be7 9. Be3 {will be back to the leading text}) 8...
a6 (8... Be7 9. h4 O-O 10. Qd2 Nde5 11. O-O-O Ng4 12. Rh3 $5 (12. Ndb5 $5 {
[%csl Rd6]}) 12... Nxe3 13. Rxe3 $16) 9. h4 Be7 10. f4 $5 (10. Qd2 O-O 11.
O-O-O $16) 10... O-O 11. h5 Nc5 (11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 e5 13. Qd2 exf4 14. Bxf4
Ne5 15. O-O-O $18) 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. h6 g6 14. Bxc5 dxc5 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. e5
Rd4 (16... Rb8 17. b3) 17. Ne2 Rb4 18. b3 $18) 7. g5 Nfd7 8. h4 {The most
consistent continuation - this pawn reaches the h4-square in one go, which,
compared to the popular line with 6.h3 against the Najdorf, will mean an extra
move in the relevant variations. In the ensuing mutual race, each tempo is
counting.} ({Like before,} 8. Be3 b5 9. a3 {is simply about to transpose.})
8... b5 9. a3 Bb7 10. Be3 Nc6 (10... Be7 11. f4 $5 (11. Qd2 Nc6 {does not
differ from the main line})) (10... Nc5 11. f3 ({another option is} 11. Bg2 {
although it makes sense to keep the c4-square under control}) 11... Nbd7 12.
Qd2 $16 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge1c1,Gh4h5]}) ({A well-known opening trap is} 10...
Nb6 $2 11. h5 N8d7 12. g6 $1 hxg6 13. hxg6 Rxh1 14. gxf7+ Ke7 (14... Kxf7 15.
Qf3+ Qf6 16. Qxh1 $18 {[%csl Rf7]}) 15. Qg4 $1 {with a strong attack -} Qc8 16.
Qxe6+ Kd8 17. Qe8+ Kc7 18. Ne6+ Kb8 19. Nxf8 Nxf8 20. Bxb6 $18) 11. Qd2 {
Besides this castling to the long White can fastly expand on the kingside by} (
11. h5 $5 Be7 12. Rg1) ({or} 11. f4 $5) 11... Be7 12. O-O-O O-O 13. Kb1 Nc5 (
13... Rc8 $143 14. Rh3 Nc5 15. f3 $16) 14. f3 Rb8 15. h5 Nxd4 (15... b4 {
can be the logic behind Black's last move, though he has yet to create threats
after} 16. axb4 Nxb4 {, as shown by the typical White's breakthrough} 17. g6
Bf6 18. h6 $1 fxg6 $140 19. Bc4 $1 d5 {and now the spectacular} 20. Nf5 $1 ({or
} 20. Qh2 gxh6 $140 21. Nf5 $36) 20... gxf5 21. hxg7 Rf7 22. Bxc5 Rxg7 23. Qh6
$1 Rc8 24. Bxb4 Rxc4 25. e5 $1 Bg5 26. Qxe6+ Kh8 27. Nxd5 Bxd5 28. Rxd5 Qg8 29.
Qxg8+ Kxg8 30. Bc3 {with every chance to convert the advantage.}) 16. Qxd4 Qc7
17. Bh3 $16 {[%cal Gg5g6] White has evidently achieved more on "his flank."} *

