1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g4 $1 e5 {The other
quick central push against the Keres attack provides Black with more chances
to initiate counterplay. However, the main drawback is quite obvious - the
weakened central d5-square. The resulting positions must also be compared to
the Perenyi gambit in the Najdorf variation 5...a6 6.Be3 e6 7.g4 and the
similar 7...e5, which is aimed at material gain.} 7. Nf5 h5 (7... Nc6 {does
not look attractive for Black after the natural} 8. Bg5 h6 $140 ({or} 8... Be6
9. Qf3 $5 h6 10. Bxf6 Qxf6 11. h4 O-O-O 12. O-O-O Kb8 13. Kb1 $16) 9. Bxf6 Qxf6
10. Nd5 Qd8 11. h4 g6 12. Nfe3 Be6 {Azarov - Nisipeanu, Aix les Bains, 2011}
13. Qf3 Bg7 (13... Nd4 14. Nf6+ Ke7 15. Ned5+ Bxd5 16. Nxd5+ Ke8 17. Qd3 $16) (
13... Be7 14. Qg3 $16) 14. c3 O-O 15. h5 Ne7 16. Bc4 $16) ({Here} 7... g6 {
, unlike in the abovementioned move order, does not require White to think
about sacrifices, for the e3-square is free for} 8. Ne3 Nc6 (8... Be6 9. g5 Nh5
10. Ned5 $16) 9. h4 Be6 10. g5 Nh5 11. Ncd5 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. Be2 Nf4 14. Ng4
Nxd5 (14... Bxd5 15. exd5 Ne7 16. Bxf4 exf4 17. Qd2 $16) 15. exd5 Bxg4 16. Bxg4
{and White keeps the upper hand. A very instructive line is} Na5 $6 17. b3 $1 {
(restricting the knight for long!)} e4 {and now the clever sacrifice} 18. Be3
$1 Bxc3+ 19. Kf1 b5 20. Rc1 Bg7 21. Qc2 Re8 22. h5 $16 {[%csl Ra5]}) 8. Bg5 $1
{Here is another difference to the mentioned sharp Najdorf line - the bishop
arrives here in one go. The defender of the key d5-square is going to be
exchanged, which will lead to a long-term White's preponderance on the light
squares.} hxg4 9. Nd5 Bxf5 (9... Be6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. Qxg4 $16) 10. Bxf6 gxf6
11. exf5 Bh6 {A sensible decision to activate the bishop as much as possible.
Moreover, it is not easy to propose a proper route for Nb8, often because of
the delayed development of Bf8, as witnessed by:} (11... Nd7 $6 {leads to a
classical position with an eternal Nd5 versus a passive bishop after} 12. Bb5
$1 (12. Rg1 $5) 12... Bh6 13. Qxg4 Kf8 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. Rd1 Qb5 16. b3 Qa5+
17. Qb4 Qxb4+ 18. Nxb4 $16 {with considerable strategical advantage}) (11... a6
$6 12. a4 Nd7 13. a5 {secures the dominating position of Nd5}) (11... Nc6 $6
12. c3 {[%csl Rc6] and Black's best seems to prepare a trade from the
e7-square.}) 12. h4 $1 {An important resource!} ({White can throw away all his
efforts by} 12. Bb5+ $6 Kf8 {(/\Bg5)}) ({or} 12. c3 $6 Bg5 {- in both cases
Black is consolidating his kingside.}) 12... gxh3 {This capture is more or
less obligatory.} ({After} 12... Nd7 13. Rg1 Nb6 14. Rxg4 Rc8 15. Bg2 $16) ({or
} 12... Kf8 13. Rg1 $16 {White has all the fun.}) 13. Rxh3 Kf8 (13... Nc6 $2
14. c3 Kf8 15. Qf3 $18) 14. Bg2 {Indeed, White's play should be based on his
supremacy on the light squares.} ({A journey like} 14. Rb3 $2 Nc6 15. Rxb7 {
as in A. Volokitin - G. Papp, Mamaia 2012, can be described as bizarre at
least - Black can take over the initiative by} Qc8 $17) (14. Qf3 $5 Nd7 15. Bd3
Nb6 16. Ke2 $16 {is yet another example of the correct strategy.}) 14... Nc6 (
14... Nd7 $6 15. Ke2 Kg7 {prepares Bh6-g5, but the king can unnoticeably find
itself in grave danger after} 16. Qd3 Bg5 $6 (16... Nc5 17. Qc4) 17. Rxh8 Qxh8
18. Rh1 Qc8 19. Kf1 $18 {[%cal Gd3h3]}) 15. Be4 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4]} Kg7 16. Qg4+
Bg5 17. Rxh8 Qxh8 18. Ke2 Qh4 19. Qxh4 Bxh4 20. c3 Bg5 21. Rd1 Rd8 22. b4 Rd7
23. a4 $16 *

