1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. g4 h6 7. Rg1 $5 ({
White's most popular move order is} 7. h4 Nc6 8. Rg1 {with probable
transposition.}) 7... Nc6 (7... g5 {is tempting, but it does not establish the
desired blockade after the vigorous thrust} 8. h4 $1 Rg8 (8... gxh4 9. g5 hxg5
10. Bxg5 $16) 9. hxg5 hxg5 10. Be3 Nc6 11. Qd2 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Be7 13. O-O-O Bd7
14. f3 a6 15. Kb1 Bc6 16. Rh1 Qc7 17. Be2 O-O-O 18. Rh6 Nd7 19. Rh7 Rgf8 20. a3
$16) (7... e5 {, regarding White's last move, which has protected the g4-pawn,
looks suspicious, though the first player has yet to prove that.} 8. Nb3 $1 (8.
Nf5 Nc6 $13) (8. Bb5+ {is positionally sound, for instance} Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7
10. Nb3 $14) 8... Be6 9. Be3 {and now:} d5 {looks as the most consistent
continuation, but Black is facing a long-term defensive task after} (9... Nc6
10. Qe2 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) (9... a6 10. h4 (10. Qf3 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4]}) 10...
d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 (12... Bxd5 13. Qe2 $16) 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 14. O-O-O
Bf3 15. Rd3 Be4 16. Rc3 Nc6 17. Nc5 Bxc5 18. Bxc5 $16) ({if} 9... Be7 {, then
White can switch to} 10. Qf3 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1]} (10. h4 $6 Nh7 $1 {[%csl Rh4]})
10... Nbd7 11. O-O-O $16 {[%cal Gh2h4]}) 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 (11...
Bxd5 12. Qe2 $16 {[%cal Ge1c1]}) 12. Qxd5 Bxd5 13. O-O-O Bf3 14. Rd3 Nd7 15.
Nd2 Bc6 16. Nc4 $16 {, which, similarly to the aforementioned line with 9...a6
10.h4 d5, is about to result in an ending with a powerful pair of White's
bishops.}) (7... a6 8. h4 d5 (8... Nfd7 9. g5 hxg5 10. hxg5 g6 11. Be3 b5 12.
a3 Bb7 13. Qd2 (13. f4 Nc5 14. Qg4 $16) 13... Nc5 14. f3 {and, unlike its
counterpart, it is hard for Black to find a safe place for his monarch -} Nbd7
15. O-O-O Rc8 16. Kb1 Qc7 17. Be2 $16 {B. Vuckovic - B. Damljanovic,
Kragujevac, 2016}) 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. Be3 (11. c3 $5) 11... e5 (
11... Be7 12. Qd2 $1 {and the assessment from above can be attached to} Bxh4 $2
{from Harikrishna - Kempinski, Germany 2016, as well, for example} 13. Bg2 Qd6
14. O-O-O Nd7 15. Kb1 Be7 16. Qe2 $18) 12. Nb3 Qxd1+ 13. Rxd1 Nc6 14. h5 Be7
15. Bg2 {with White's lasting edge -} Be6 16. Be4 Rd8 17. Nc5 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1
Bxc5 19. Bxc5 Kd7 20. Ke2 Kc7 21. Bf5 Bd5 22. b3 $16) (7... Be7 8. Be3 {
is likely to transpose later.}) 8. Be3 (8. h4 {- 7.h4.}) 8... Be7 ({In reply to
} 8... Bd7 {White has time for the preparatory} 9. Be2 $5 (9. h4 h5 10. gxh5
Rxh5 11. Bg5 $36) 9... Be7 (9... e5 $6 {is too strategically obliging, for
example} 10. Ndb5 Be6 11. Nd5 $16) (9... a6 10. h4 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5
exd5 {and now the old, but sound idea} 13. Qd2 $5 Qxh4 14. O-O-O O-O-O 15. Bf3
{with ample compensation for the pawn. Here is an example of how quickly Black
can go astray -} Bc5 $6 (15... Bb4 16. Qd3 Ne5 17. Qb3 Nxf3 18. Nxf3 Qe7 19.
Bb6 Rde8 20. Qxd5 $16) 16. Qc3 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 f6 $2 18. Be3 $1 $18 {Velimirovic
- Bertok, Vinkovci, 1970}) 10. Qd2 (10. h4 d5 11. exd5 Nxd5 12. Nxd5 exd5 13.
Qd2 Bxh4 14. O-O-O $16 {is quite similar to the line from above}) 10... a6 11.
h4 $16) (8... e5 $6 9. Nb3 (9. Nxc6 $2 bxc6 10. Bc4 Rb8 11. Bb3 Be6 12. Qe2 $16
) 9... Be6 10. Qe2 Be7 11. O-O-O $16) ({the other central push} 8... d5 $6 {
is once again dubious -} 9. Bb5 Bd7 10. exd5 exd5 11. Qe2 $16) ({in case of} 
8... a6 {the events can take an original course after} 9. Nxc6 $5 ({the common
theoretical move is} 9. h4) 9... bxc6 10. Qf3 {(/\0-0-0)} Rb8 (10... d5 11.
O-O-O) (10... Be7 11. h4 $16) 11. O-O-O Qc7 12. h4 d5 13. g5 hxg5 14. hxg5 Nd7
15. g6 f6 16. Kb1 Qa5 17. Bc1 $16) 9. Qe2 $5 {The already common plan with
castling to the long.} (9. h4 d5 $13) ({As we are going to see, the text move
is much more venomous than the routine} 9. Qd2) 9... Nxd4 (9... a6 $6 10. O-O-O
Qc7 11. f4 $16) 10. Bxd4 e5 11. Be3 Be6 12. O-O-O Nd7 (12... Rc8 {is nicely
answered with} 13. Qb5+ $1 Qd7 $140 14. Bxa7 $1 Bxg4 (14... Rxc3 $143 15. bxc3
Nxe4 16. Kb2 d5 17. a4 Nd6 18. Bb6 $16) 15. Qxd7+ Bxd7 16. f3 $16) ({After} 
12... a6 13. h4 {White's expansion seems unstoppable, e.g.} Nh7 14. f4 $16) 13.
h4 $5 {An original approach.} ({It is early for} 13. Nb5 Nb6 $13) ({, but the
useful prophylactic move} 13. Kb1 {is fully playable.}) 13... Bxh4 {This
capture stops the kingside assault, though it leads by force to a position
with a pair of bishops and continuous pressure for White.} ({The attempt to
initiate counterattack on the queenside by means of} 13... Rc8 {seems to fall
short, for example} 14. g5 hxg5 15. hxg5 Rxc3 (15... Qa5 16. Qb5 $1) 16. bxc3
Qc7 (16... Qa5 17. Qb5 Qxc3 18. g6 $16) 17. g6 fxg6 18. Rxg6 Nf6 19. Qd3 Kf7
20. Rg3 Qa5 21. Bg5 $16 Qxa2 $140 22. Qf3 {[%cal Gf1d3] and White is about to
consolidate and create threats along the g-file.}) 14. Nb5 $1 Be7 15. Nxd6+
Bxd6 16. Rxd6 Qa5 17. a3 Ke7 (17... O-O-O 18. g5 {Krueger - Juarez de Vena,
ICCF email, 2016,} hxg5 19. Bxg5 Rdg8 20. Kb1 $36) ({Black's king has also
remained in the center after} 17... Rc8 18. g5 hxg5 19. Bxg5 Qc7 (19... Nc5 20.
Kb1 $16) 20. Qd1 $1 Nc5 (20... a6 21. Kb1 $16) 21. Bb5+ Kf8 22. Kb1 $16 {
Broudin - Mesquita, ICCF email, 2012. He will suffer a lot even after the
relatively best} Rh2 (22... a6 $2 {fails to the exciting maneuver} 23. Bd8 Qb8
24. Bb6 $1 {with the magnificent final strike at the end of the possible line}
axb5 25. Bxc5 Kg8 26. Rxe6 Rxc5 27. Rd6 Rc8 28. Qg4 $1 Rh7 29. Rh6 $3 {By far
not an ordinary way to trap and win a rook!}) (22... Nxe4 23. Rxe6 Nxg5 24. Rd6
{/\Rd7|^}) 23. Be3 Nxe4 24. Rxe6 fxe6 25. Bd7 Rd8 26. Qf3+ Nf6 27. Bxe6 b6 28.
Bb3 $36) 18. Rxe6+ $5 {An original exchange sacrifice, by which White succeeds
for the g4-g5 break.} ({After} 18. Bd2 Qc7 19. Rd3 f6 20. Rc3 Qb6 21. Be3 Qa5
22. Qd2 Rhc8 {Black has managed to disable it and White's temporary initiative
and keep the balance -} 23. Rxc8 Qxd2+ 24. Kxd2 Rxc8 25. f3 Nc5 $11 {in
Sospedra Sebastian - Sneppe, ICCF email, 2020, which was drawn soon.}) 18...
fxe6 (18... Kxe6 19. g5 $36) 19. g5 h5 20. g6 $44 Rac8 21. Bd2 Qc7 22. Bb4+ Nc5
23. Kb1 a5 24. Bd2 $40 *

