1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 {The ultra-popular Najdorf
variation. In this database, I will suggest a repertoire based on} 6. Bd3 {
, which has lately gained much in popularity. As usual, the review starts with
observing the minor alternatives.} Nbd7 {, being the first:} (6... Qb6 $6 {
does not attack anything and White has a good reason to seize space by} 7. a4
$5 $146 (7. O-O) 7... Nc6 (7... e6 8. a5) (7... e5 8. Nde2 {[%csl Rb6][%cal
Ga4a5]}) 8. Nxc6 bxc6 9. a5 Qc7 10. Be3 $16 {More about such a position can be
found in Chapter 16 in the notes to a similar sally 7...Qb6}) (6... Bd7 {
is correlated more with the classical Sicilian or the Dragon, so 7...Nc6 can
be expected to come next. White can adequately react with} 7. f4 Nc6 8. Nf3 {
with a scheme in which Black's move 6 may prove useless.} (8. e5 $5 {is worth
checking}) 8... g6 9. O-O Bg7 10. h3 {Both useful (preparing the next move)
and restricting measure.} O-O 11. Be3 Rc8 (11... b5 12. Qd2 Qc7 13. Rad1 $14)
12. Qe1 Nb4 (12... b5 13. a4) 13. a3 Nxd3 14. cxd3 $14 {[%cal Ge1f2]}) ({
the harsh} 6... b5 $6 {is dubious against nearly all White's options on move 6
against the Najdorf and even when the e4-pawn is not overprotected. The common
reaction is} 7. Nd5 $1 {, here Black is lacking a satisfactory answer as well -
} e5 (7... Nxd5 8. exd5 Bb7 9. c4 $16) (7... e6 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. O-O Bb7 10. a4
$16) (7... Bb7 8. Nxf6+ gxf6 9. a4 $16) 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Ne2 Bb7 10. c4 $16) (
6... Qc7 {is likely to anticipate the set-ups with f2-f4, so it makes sense
for White to prefer} 7. Be3 ({in reply to} 7. f4 {Black can even go for} b5 $13
) ({White, in his turn, may discourage this early thrust by simply developing -
} 7. O-O) ({or just exclude it by} 7. a4) 7... e6 (7... e5 8. Nb3 Be6 {is
quite typical for the normal Najdorf, but right here, a hidden argument in
favor of the location of Bd3 and its defensive function of the central pawn is
revealed by the unexpected} 9. Na4 $1 Nbd7 10. c4 Bxc4 11. Rc1 Bxb3 12. Qxb3
Nc5 13. O-O $1 {and White regains the pawn with interest -} Be7 14. Qc2 Qc6 (
14... Qd8 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. Rfd1 $36) 15. Nxc5 dxc5 16. Bxc5 Rc8 17. Be3 Qxc2
18. Bxc2 O-O 19. Bb1 $14 {with a small but lasting edge due to the pair of
bishops}) 8. a4 (8. g4 $5 {deserves attention because any ideas for material
gain with e6-e5 should fall short}) 8... Nc6 (8... b6 9. g4 $1 $36) 9. f4 Be7
10. O-O O-O {with a better version of the classical Scheveningen, for instance}
11. Kh1 Bd7 12. Qf3 $14) (6... Nc6 {in the spirit of the classical Sicilian
looks natural, but White has the new plan with} 7. Nxc6 $1 ({Black does not
experience problems after both} 7. Be3 e5) ({and} 7. Nb3 g6 {, while the text
move is trying to prove that a7-a6 is just idle}) 7... bxc6 {and now} 8. b3 $1
{[%cal Gc1b2] , which is a reminiscence of the original anti-Najdorf plan with
2.Nc3 d6 3.d4!? After} g6 ({in case of the committing push} 8... e5 {White is
by no means obliged to fianchetto the bishop; instead, he can continue with} 9.
O-O Be7 10. Qe2 O-O 11. Na4 $14 {[%cal Gc2c4]}) 9. Bb2 Bg7 {White must be
consequent with} 10. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1]} ({rather than} 10. Na4 Qa5+ $5 11.
Bc3 Qg5 $13) ({or} 10. O-O) 10... Nd7 {is practically inviting the trade of
the dark-squared bishops -} (10... O-O 11. O-O-O a5 12. Na4 (12. f4 $5 {
is a plausible alternative}) 12... d5 13. e5 Nd7 14. Qe3 Qc7 15. f4 {The
situation in the center has more or less clarified; Black should avoid the
grip over the queenside dark squares by mean of} c5 {, but he seems to be
behind in the mutual race after} 16. h4 $40 {Paravyan - Ponomariov, Douglas,
2019}) 11. Na4 Bxb2 12. Nxb2 Nc5 13. O-O (13. h4 $5 h5) 13... O-O 14. Rfe1 $14
{[%cal Ga1d1,Gd3f1]}) 7. Be3 $5 {Just like after 6...Qc7, White has a choice
between the text,} (7. O-O) ({and} 7. a4) 7... e6 (7... g6 8. f3 Bg7 9. Qd2 {
transposes to the next Chapter, which is dealing with 6...g6.}) 8. a4 b6 {
The prevention of the blockading 9.a5 is most probably Black's best.} (8... Be7
9. a5 O-O 10. Nb3 Ne5 11. Be2 Qc7 (11... Bd7 12. f4 Ng6 13. g3 $14) (11... d5
$6 12. Bb6 Qe8 {in Esipenko - Murzin, Sochi, 2020, can be seriously questioned
by} 13. exd5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Qxd5 $16) 12. Bb6 Qb8 13. f4 Ned7 14. Bf2
b5 15. axb6 Nxb6 16. Na5 Qc7 17. O-O Rb8 18. Qd3 $14) 9. g4 $5 $146 h6 ({
Risky is} 9... h5 $6 10. g5 Ng4 11. Bd2 $36 {Ng4 will also be chased back to
its camp after}) (9... Ne5 $6 10. g5 Nfg4 11. Bc1 Nxd3+ 12. cxd3 Ne5 13. f4 Nd7
14. Be3 $16) 10. h4 Bb7 ({It is possible to insert} 10... Nc5 11. f3 {before}
Bb7 {, then White has the unusual regrouping of the own bishop} 12. Bc4 $1 Qc7
13. Qe2 $36 {[%csl Rc5][%cal Ge1c1] at his disposal, with the least idea to
deprive the opponent of the opportunity to trade minor pieces.}) 11. Rg1 {
With the explicit intention to march to the g6-square, to which Black can
follow the famous principle for a central counterstrike with} d5 (11... Ne5 12.
f4 Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3 Nd7 14. Bf2 Nc5 15. Qe3 $36) 12. g5 {Nevertheless!} hxg5 13.
hxg5 Nxe4 ({Alternatively,} 13... dxe4 14. gxf6 exd3 15. fxg7 Bxg7 16. Qxd3 Nc5
17. Qc4 Be5 18. O-O-O $14 {with rich attacking possibilities.}) 14. g6 $1 Qf6 (
14... Ndf6 15. gxf7+ Kxf7 16. Nf3 $5 (16. Qe2 $44) 16... Kg8 17. Bd4 $40) 15.
gxf7+ Qxf7 16. Bxe4 dxe4 17. Qe2 Ne5 18. O-O-O $44 O-O-O ({If the king remains
in the center, it is no wonder that the tactics will work entirely for White,
e.g.} 18... Bb4 19. Nxe4 $1 Bxe4 20. Bg5 Qb7 21. f3 Nxf3 22. Nxf3 Bc5 23. Rg4
$1 Bf5 24. Rf4 O-O 25. Rh4 $40) ({No better are the continuations} 18... Be7
19. Nb3) ({and} 18... Rd8 19. Nb3 $14 {, when in both cases the b6-pawn is in
trouble.}) 19. Nb3 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Qc7 21. Nd2 Bb4 22. Ncxe4 Kb8 23. c3 $14 *

