a4 Be7 11. Kh1 O-O 12. Be3 Rac8 13. a5 exf4 (13... Rfe8 14. h3 $5) (13... Rfd8
14. h3 $14) 14. Nxf4 Ne5 15. Bd4 $14) 9. Nxf4 Nbd7 {Both routes of the knight
to the center have their merits.} (9... Nc6 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Bc4 $1 {[%csl
Re6]} Qd7 12. Bb3 Be7 (12... O-O-O 13. Bg5 Be7 14. Qe2 $36) 13. Bf4 Rd8 ({
in case of} 13... O-O {White stays on top by force after} 14. e5 $1 Ne4 15.
Nxe4 Rxf4 16. Nc5 Qe8 17. Nxe6 (17. exd6 $2 Rd8 $17) 17... Re4+ 18. Kf2 Kh8 19.
Qf3 Rxe5 20. Rhe1 Bf6 21. c3 $14) 14. Qd3 ({worth checking is to secure the
bishop with} 14. a3 $5 {[%csl Rb3]}) 14... Na5 (14... O-O 15. O-O-O) 15. O-O-O
Nxb3+ 16. axb3 O-O 17. e5 dxe5 18. Qe2 Qc6 19. Bxe5 $14) (9... Be7 10. Nxe6
fxe6 11. Bc4 Qd7 12. Bf4 Nc6 13. Bb3 {- 9... Nc6.}) 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Qe2 $1 {
White mobilizes his army without any delay.} (11. Bc4 Nxe4 $1 (11... Nc5 $6 12.
Be3 $16) 12. Qh5+ (12. Qg4 Nxc3 13. Qxe6+ Qe7 14. bxc3 Nc5 15. Qxe7+ Bxe7 $11)
(12. O-O Nxc3 13. bxc3 d5 $13) (12. Nxe4 $2 Qh4+) 12... g6 13. Qh3 (13. Qg4 {
does not differ after} Nxc3) 13... Nxc3 14. Qxe6+ (14. bxc3 Qf6 {is also about
to transpose}) 14... Qe7 15. bxc3 Qxe6+ 16. Bxe6 Bg7 17. Bd2 Nc5 18. Bd5 Rf8
19. O-O-O O-O-O $13) 11... Ne5 12. Bf4 $1 ({Here} 12. Bc4 {, which has taken
place in W. Watson - M. Chandler, Germany, 1996, is neutralized in the spirit
of the 6.f4 Najdorf with} Nxc4 $1 13. Qxc4 Qc8 14. Qb3 Be7 $11) 12... Qc7 (
12... Be7 13. O-O-O Qc7 {just transposes to an inferior line, see below.}) 13.
O-O-O b5 {This typical Sicilian push is also aimed at restricting Bd3, a
sample line is} (13... Be7 $143 14. Bxe5 $1 dxe5 15. Bc4 Qc6 16. Rhf1 $14 O-O
$140 $6 17. Rf5 $1) 14. Bxe5 ({An alternative is} 14. Nb1 $5 {with probable
transposition to the text.}) 14... dxe5 15. Nb1 $5 {[%cal Gb1d2] Before even
thinking about his queenside majority, White must first improve his minor
pieces.} ({Here is a very entertaining sample line, in which White first
demonstrates aggressive intentions on the opposite side of the board -} 15. g4
Ba3 $1 16. Nxb5 ({it is not that late for White to revert to the idea for} 16.
Nb1) 16... axb5 17. Bxb5+ Ke7 18. g5 (18. bxa3 Qc5) 18... Nd5 $1 19. exd5 Qc3
$1 20. d6+ ({Black is forcing perpetual after} 20. bxa3 Qxa3+ 21. Kd2 $8 Qb4+
22. Kc1 $8 Qa3+ 23. Kd2 $8 $11) 20... Kd8 21. Qd3 Qxb2+ 22. Kd2 Rf8 $1 23. Rhf1
Rf4 $1 24. Rb1 (24. Rxf4 exf4 25. Ke2 Ra5 $13) 24... Qd4 {and, due to the
opposite-colored bishops, a draw is the most likely outcome -} 25. Ke2 Bxd6 26.
Rxf4 Qxd3+ 27. Kxd3 Ra3+ 28. Rb3 exf4 $11) 15... Be7 (15... Qa5 16. a3) 16. Nd2
O-O 17. Kb1 Rad8 18. c3 Rd6 19. Nb3 $14 *

