1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 e5 7. Nde2 Nc6 8.
O-O (8. Nd5 {is possible, but White does not need to hurry with this jump,
after} Nxd5 9. exd5 Nb4 (9... Qa5+ 10. Nc3) 10. Be4 (10. Bc4 Bf5 11. Bb3 a5 $13
) 10... a5 $1 (10... f5 $143 11. a3 $1) 11. c3 Na6 $13 {the knight will be
well placed on the c5-square. See more on this item in the next Chapter.}) 8...
Be6 (8... d5 $6 {is insufficient in the view of} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11.
Nc3 Qd8 12. Be3 Be6 13. Qe2 Nd4 (13... Be7 14. Rad1 $16) 14. Qe1 $16 {/\Rd1.})
(8... Be7 {will be examined in the next Chapter.}) 9. Kh1 $1 ({The plan with} 
9. f4 exf4 10. Nxf4 {has been analyzed in the previous Chapter, but White has
already castled here. After} Ne5 11. a4 g6 $1 {[%cal Gf8g7] Black seems pretty
solid -} 12. Be3 (12. Be2 Bg7 13. Be3 O-O 14. a5 Rc8 15. Ra4 Re8 $132 {proved
balanced in Svidler - Shankland, Saint Louis, 2021}) 12... Bg7 13. a5 O-O $13)
9... Rc8 $5 $146 {A smart idea to complete the mobilization of the queenside
before committing Bf8.} ({Here is a better moment for} 9... d5 10. exd5 $140
Nxd5 11. Nxd5 {, but White retains some initiative after} Bxd5 12. Nc3 Be6 13.
f4 $14) (9... Nb4 $6 10. f4 Nxd3 {costs much time and White has the upper hand
-} 11. Qxd3 Rc8 12. b3 {[%cal Gf4f5]} Be7 13. f5 $5 (13. a4 $14) 13... Bd7 14.
Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 b5 16. Ng3 $36) (9... g6 $6 {is premature because of} 10. Bg5
$1 Bg7 {and only now} 11. f4 exf4 12. Nxf4 h6 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15.
Qg4 Kf7 16. Bc4 Qe7 17. Qh3 Raf8 18. Rad1 $40) (9... Be7 $5 {is, similarly to
one move earlier, transposing again -} 10. f4 exf4 11. Nxf4 {etc.}) 10. Nd5 $5
{A very interesting pawn sacrifice, drastically changing the situation.} ({
Analogously to Svidler - Shankland from above,} 10. f4 exf4 11. Nxf4 Ne5 12.
Be3 {is adequately met by} g6 $1 {and "the snake" manoeuvre} 13. Bf2 $5 {
[%cal Gf2h4]} Bg7 14. Bh4 {is neutralized by} Qd7 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Ncd5 (16.
Nxe6 Qxe6 17. Nd5 Bg5 $11) 16... Bd8 17. c3 O-O $11) 10... Nxd5 11. exd5 Bxd5
12. f4 Be6 $1 ({The move order with} 12... Ne7 13. Nc3 Be6 {seems to be less
precise:} 14. f5 $1 {is the acid test, as shown by:} (14. Qf3 d5 15. fxe5 (15.
f5 e4) 15... Ng6 $13) 14... Bc4 (14... Bd7 $2 15. Bg5 (15. f6 $5 gxf6 16. Qh5
$40) 15... Bc6 16. f6 gxf6 17. Rxf6 $16) 15. Qf3 $1 ({a curious idea instead
of the natural} 15. f6 $5 gxf6 16. Bxc4 Rxc4 17. Rxf6 {, which is spelling
danger}) 15... f6 ({in reply to} 15... Qd7 $6 {White has no reason to postpone}
16. Bxc4 Rxc4 17. f6 $16) 16. Be3 $1 Qd7 17. Be4 $1 Bxf1 18. Qh5+ $5 (18. Rxf1
$40) 18... g6 19. fxg6 hxg6 20. Qxh8 Bc4 21. Qxf6 Qe6 {and White can liquidate
to an endgame with an extra pawn -} 22. Qxe6 Bxe6 23. Bxb7 Rb8 24. Bxa6 Rxb2
25. Bd3 Bg7 26. a4 $16) (12... g6 {is a bit risky, as it helps the opponent to
open the f-file by means of} 13. Nc3 $1 (13. f5 Nb4 $13) 13... Be6 14. f5 gxf5
15. Bxf5 Bxf5 (15... Qd7 $2 16. Nd5 $18) (15... Qh4 16. Be3 $44) 16. Rxf5 Qd7 (
16... Nd4 $6 17. Rf1 Bg7 18. Qg4 $16) 17. Qh5 Nd4 18. Rf2 Qe6 19. Bg5 Qg6 20.
Qh4 $44) 13. f5 Bd7 14. Nc3 ({White can begin with} 14. Be4 {, to which Black
can give the pawn back by} Ne7 $1 15. Bxb7 ({there is also} 15. Qxd6 f6 $1 16.
Nc3 Bc6 17. Qe6 Qd7 $11) (15. Nc3 d5 {is going to transpose to 14.Nc3}) 15...
Rc7 16. Be4 d5 $1 17. Bxd5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Bb5 19. Qxd8+ (19. Qxe5+ $2 {is
losing a piece after} Re7 {[%csl Re2]}) 19... Kxd8 20. Rd1+ Rd7 $44) (14. c4
Nb4 15. Bb1 Be7 $13) 14... Nb4 $1 {As we already know from the comments to 12..
.Ne7, now this square is abandoned for the knight. Besides the text move,
which continues the fight for the center,} ({Black can keep the f6- and
g5-squares under control by both} 14... Nd4 15. Be3 $44) ({and} 14... Be7 15.
Be4 $44) 15. Be4 d5 $1 {In combination with the previous move - the key
