f4 O-O $15) 9... Nxd5 10. exd5 Nb4 11. Be4 $1 {We have already seen of this
without 0-0 and Bf8-e7.} ({Here too,} 11. Bc4 {fails to impress in the view of}
Bf5 12. Bb3 Rc8 13. Nc3 a5 $13) 11... f5 (11... a5 12. c3 $140 Na6 {is once
again a major alternative -} 13. f4 {and now:} O-O {is relatively best, if not
the only, but White's kingside initiative is ongoing -} (13... Nc5 14. Bc2 O-O
15. Ng3 $36) (13... f5 $2 14. fxe5 $1 {sacrifices a piece, in return Black's
position will be divided into two parts by the wedge on the e6-square, as
illustrated by:} Qb6+ (14... fxe4 15. e6 (15. Nd4 $5) 15... Qb6+ 16. Nd4 {
can transpose to the line below, while the immediate} Qc5 {is running into the
trap} 17. Be3 Qxd5 18. Qa4+ Kd8 19. Rf5 $18) 15. Kh1 fxe4 16. e6 Nc7 17. Nd4
Qc5 {is getting close to the central pawns, but White's offensive prevails
after} 18. Rf7 $1 Nxd5 19. Bg5 $3 g6 (19... Bxg5 20. Qh5 g6 21. Qxg5 $18) 20.
Nb3 Qc6 {and now the resolute queen sacrifice} 21. Qxd5 $1 {with full
domination after} Qxd5 22. Rxe7+ Kf8 23. Rf1+ Qf5 24. Rxf5+ gxf5 25. Nd4 $18) (
13... Bf6 $6 14. Qc2 $1 ({a small, but remarkable refinement over my move order
} 14. Ng3 O-O 15. Qc2 h6 16. Nh5 $16 {in Cheparinov - Murzin, Ankara, 2022,
which is also demonstrating how precarious Black's position is}) 14... h6 (
14... g6 15. f5 $1) 15. Bh7 $3 Nc5 16. Ng3 $16) 14. fxe5 (14. f5 Bg5 $13) 14...
dxe5 15. Ng3 {and now:} Nc5 (15... g6 16. Bh6 Qb6+ (16... f5 17. Bxf8 Qxf8 {
is a common exchange sacrifice in many Sicilians, but after} 18. Bc2 $16 {
it is unlikely that the blockade over the dark squares will suffice}) 17. Kh1
Re8 (17... Rd8 18. Qf3 f5 19. Bc2 $16) 18. Qf3 f5 19. d6 $1 Qxd6 20. Rad1 Qb6
21. Bd5+ Kh8 22. Bf7 Be6 23. Bxe8 Rxe8 24. b3 Nc5 25. c4 $16) 16. Bc2 Bd6 (
16... g6 17. b4 $1 $16) 17. Be3 $36) 12. a3 $1 Nc6 ({Without this tricky move
Black is simply worse -} 12... fxe4 $6 13. axb4 O-O 14. Ng3 $16) 13. dxc6 ({
If the first player prefers to keep both bishops of his on the board, then} 13.
Bd3 Nb8 14. c4 O-O $140 15. f4 $14 {has to be his choice.}) 13... fxe4 14. cxb7
Bxb7 15. c4 ({Indeed, White must fight against the enemy central pawns, and
the control over the key d5-square is substantial. It seems that White has
even enough time for} 15. Nc3 $5 Rc8 16. Nd5 Rc5 17. Ne3 O-O {and only now the
fixing} (17... d5 $2 18. Qh5+) 18. c4 Bg5 19. Qe2 $14) 15... Rc8 16. Qb3 Ba8
17. Be3 d5 18. cxd5 Bxd5 19. Qa4+ Qd7 20. Qa5 Bd8 21. Qd2 Bc4 22. Rfd1 Qxd2 23.
Rxd2 $14 *

