12. Nxf6+ Bxf6 13. Ng3 (13. c4 b5 $13) ({a plausible alternative is} 13. Nc3 $5
Nd7 14. Qg4) 13... Nd7 14. Qg4 Kh8 15. Be3 $36) 12. exd5 Bb5 $1 ({a highly
unusual shot at counterplay, while the symmetrical} 12... Bg5 $2 {may backfire
badly after} 13. Bxg5 Qxg5 14. Rf3 $18) 13. Nc3 (13. c4 e4 $1 $132 14. cxb5
exd3 15. Qxd3 (15. Nc3 axb5 16. Qxd3 b4 17. Ne4 Nd7 $11 {Gossmann - Sternik,
FICGS email, 2019}) 15... Bf6 16. Nc3 Re8 {with ample compensation for the
pawn -} 17. Kh1 Qb6 18. Ne4 (18. Bf4 Nd7 $44) (18. bxa6 Qxa6 19. Qxa6 Nxa6 20.
Bf4 Nb4 21. Bxd6 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Nxd5 23. c4 Ne3 $11) 18... Nd7 $44) (13. Bxb5
axb5 14. Qd3 {is countered in the same manner -} Nd7 $1 (14... b4 $143 15. Qb3)
15. Qxb5 Qb6+ 16. Qxb6 Nxb6 17. Rd1 Rfc8 18. c3 Na4 $44) 13... Bxd3 14. cxd3 {
seems to be the critical continuation, Black should tread carefully, as
revealed by the sample lines} Nd7 15. Rf3 Nf6 16. Rg3 Kh8 17. Be3 Rc8 18. Qe2
Qa5 19. Rf1 Rfe8 (19... Nxd5 $2 20. Qg4 Bf6 21. Bg5 $18) 20. Rh3 $36) (10. a4 {
may lead to the main text, compared to the exciting line with 10.Kh1, see
below, Black has no concern about the potential Nc3-a4} exf4) 10... exf4 11.
Nxf4 Nc6 {is quite similar to the leading text, Black's castling appears to be
a precondition for the dangerous try} 12. Nxe6 (12. Be3 Ne5 13. a4 {is the
main line}) 12... fxe6 13. Bc4 Qd7 14. Na4 Bd8 15. Bf4 {, to which Black has
the instructive reaction} Re8 $1 (15... Nxe4 $6 16. Bd3 Nf6 17. Bxd6 Be7 18.
Bg3 $14) 16. Bxd6 Bc7 $1 17. Bxc7 Qxc7 18. Bb3 Rad8 19. Qe1 Qe5 {and the
preponderance on the central dark squares is yielding Black at least enough
compensation for the sacrificed pawn.}) (9... Qc7 {has been mentioned in
Chapter 18 as well, then} 10. Ng3 {is also an option.}) 10. Nxf4 Nc6 11. Be3 (
11. Nxe6 fxe6 12. Bc4 Qd7 13. Bf4 b5 14. Bb3 {Stany - Gopal, Biel, 2019} O-O
$11) (11. Kh1 {is about to transpose, so is with 11.a4.}) 11... Ne5 (11... O-O
$6 {is inviting} 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. Bc4 {, when} d5 ({compared to the featured
game with 11.Nxe6, here White;s dark-squared bishop controls the g1-a7
diagonal, therefore} 13... Qd7 $2 {fails to} 14. Na4 $1) 14. exd5 Ne5 15. Bb3
Neg4 {is a desperate attempt at creating a mess by fighting for the mentioned
diagonal, to which, besides protecting Be3, White has the resolute exchange
sacrifice} 16. Rxf6 $1 Nxf6 17. dxe6 $16 {with great compensation.}) 12. Kh1
O-O 13. a4 Rc8 14. a5 (14. Bd4 Nfd7 15. Ncd5 (15. a5 Nc6 $1) 15... Bg5 16. a5 {
So far Moussard - Gasic Merino, Sitges, 2022, when} Bxf4 $5 {deserves
attention -} 17. Nxf4 (17. Rxf4 $6 Nc5) 17... Nc5 18. Bc3 Qg5 $11) 14... Nfd7 {
The most consistent continuation.} (14... Rc6 $6 {has been tested at the
highest level -} 15. Ncd5 Re8 16. b3 ({as soon as the c6-square is occupied,} 
16. Bd4 $5 {comes into consideration -} Nfd7 17. b3) (16. h3 $5) 16... Nxd3 17.
Qxd3 Bxd5 $6 ({Black should have reconciled himself with the slightly cramped
position after} 17... Nd7 18. Bd4 Ne5 19. Qd1 Bg5 20. c4 $14) 18. Nxd5 (18.
exd5 $5 Rc8 19. Bd4 $16) 18... Nxd5 19. exd5 Rc8 20. Bd4 Qd7 21. c4 $16 {
Karjakin - Svidler, Lichess.org INT, 2022}) (14... Nc4 $6 {is a bit premature -
} 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 (15... Bxc4 16. Rf3 {[%cal Gf3g3]}) 16. Bd4 Nd7 (16... Qc8 $6 {
Willow - Khandelwal, London, 2023} 17. Qd3 $16) 17. Ncd5 Bg5 18. b3 Rc8 19. c4
$14) 15. Bg1 {As we already know, on the d4-square, this bishop will be
exposed to Ne5-c6.} (15. Be2 Nc4 {is either (if White takes the knight)
gaining a tempo compared to an example from above, which will not allow the
transfer of Rf1 to the 3rd rank, or simplifies the position to an equal
endgame after} 16. Nxe6 Nxe3 17. Nxd8 Nxd1 18. Rfxd1 Rfxd8 19. Nd5 Bg5 {
, when both knights will be planted on fine central squares -} 20. c3 Rb8 $11)
(15. Ncd5 Bg5 {is what Black has prepared by his previous move. Instead, White
will be trying to target the d6-pawn in order to hold Be7 at place.}) 15... Re8
{Yet another useful mobilizing move, Nd7 may still have to cover the b6-square,
} ({as shown by} 15... Nc5 16. Be2 Bg5 17. Nfd5 $14 {[%csl Rb6]}) ({or} 15...
Bg5 $5 16. Be2 Nf6 17. Ra4 $14) 16. Be2 $5 {[%csl Rd6] Played in accordance
with the last comment, White is also clearing the 3rd rank.} ({As before,} 16.
Ncd5 Bg5 {is roughly balanced.}) 16... h6 (16... Nc4 17. Ncd5 Bg5 (17... Nxb2
$2 18. Qb1 Nc4 19. Qxb7 $18) 18. Qd4 Nde5 19. b4 $14) 17. Ncd5 {Only now -
White has an additional option for} Bg5 18. Ra3 $14 {[%cal Ga3g3]} *

