1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 a6 6. Bd3 e5 7. Nde2 Be7 8.
O-O O-O 9. Ng3 Bg4 $5 {A little provocation before the bishop comes to the
usual e6-square. Indeed, 9...Be6 is the main move; here we will mention its
minor alternatives:} (9... Nc6 $6 10. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 (10... Be6 $6 11. c4 $16) 11.
exd5 Nb8 (11... Nb4 $6 12. Bf5 $1 ({taking advantage of the successful
knight's transfer rather than the feeble} 12. Be2 a5) 12... a5 13. c3 Na6 14.
f4 {and now:} Nc5 (14... Bf6 {K. Arjun - V. Spitzl, Riga, 2021, White has a
pleasant choice -} 15. Bc2 $5 ({or} 15. Be3 Nc5 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. f5 $16) 15...
Nc5 16. Nh5 $16) 15. fxe5 dxe5 {So far Thorfinnsson - Steingrimsson, Selfoss,
2022,} 16. Bxc8 Rxc8 17. Nf5 Bf6 18. d6 (18. Be3 g6 19. Nh6+ Kg7 20. Qe2 $16 {
looks very promising either}) 18... Qd7 19. Be3 Qe6 20. Qg4 Kh8 21. Rad1 $16)
12. f4 Nd7 (12... exf4 13. Bxf4 Nd7 14. Nf5 Ne5 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Qd2 $14 {
[%csl Rd6][%cal Ga1e1]}) 13. f5 $5 ({an interesting, though the slightly
obliging idea to establish blockade on the e4-square as a stepping-stone for
the pieces in the kingside assault; White does not benefit from} 13. Nf5 $6 Bf6
) ({, besides, the prophylactic} 13. Kh1 $5) ({or the solid option} 13. c4 $5 {
can be preferred}) 13... b5 ({it early for Black to commit his Nd7, for
instance} 13... Nf6 14. Qf3 b5 15. Bg5 $36) ({or} 13... Nc5 $6 14. Be3 {
, in both cases White has prepared to plant a knight on the most desired place
on the board}) 14. Kh1 (14. Qf3 $5) 14... Bb7 (14... Nc5 15. Qg4 $40) 15. Nh5 (
15. Qf3 $5 Nf6 16. Ne4) 15... Nf6 16. Nxf6+ Bxf6 17. Be4 Bg5 (17... Rc8 18. Qg4
Re8 19. b3 $14) 18. Bxg5 (18. Qg4 f6) 18... Qxg5 19. Qe1 (19. f6 g6 {with a
probable transposition}) 19... Rac8 20. f6 g6 21. a4 {(opening a second front)}
Rc4 22. axb5 axb5 23. Ra7 Bc8 24. b3 $14) (9... Re8 10. Be3 g6 (10... Be6 11.
Nd5 $1 Bxd5 12. exd5 Nbd7 13. c4 g6 14. Rc1 h5 15. h3 $14) (10... Ng4 11. Bd2
$14) 11. Na4 $1 Nbd7 12. c4 $14 {Perez Hernandez - Mandviwala, ICCF email, 2018
}) (9... g6 {allows the clever twist} 10. Bc4 $5 (10. Bh6 Re8) 10... Be6 (10...
b5 11. Bd5 Ra7 12. Be3 Rd7 13. a3 $14) 11. Nd5 {with firm control over the key
central square -} Bxd5 12. Bxd5 Nxd5 (12... Nc6 13. c3 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 Qd7 15.
Rd1 $14 {Chigaev - Kokarev, Khanty-Mansiysk, 2019}) 13. Qxd5 Qc7 14. Ne2 $5 ({
if} 14. c3 {, then} Nd7 {is more flexible than in the latter example -} 15. Rd1
{Deac - Mekhitarian, Chess. com INT, 2021,} Qc6 $11) 14... Nd7 15. Nc3 $14) (
9... b5 10. h3 $5 Nbd7 {and now the multifunctional advance} (10... g6 11. Bh6
Re8 12. b4 $1 Nc6 13. a4 bxa4 14. Rxa4 $14) (10... Qc7 11. Bd2 $14) 11. b4 $1 (
11. Nf5 {is a bit premature in the view of} Nc5 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. Bg5 Be6 $11)
11... a5 ({Black has already to reckon with the a2-a4 break, while} 11... Bb7
12. Nf5 $36 {is also asking for trouble}) 12. Nxb5 axb4 13. Bd2 $36) 10. Be2 ({
After the minor alternative} 10. f3 Be6 {this pawn will probably have to make
the next step,}) ({as well as after} 10. Qe1 Nbd7 11. f4 exf4 12. Bxf4 Ne5 $11)
10... Be6 ({The trade} 10... Bxe2 $6 {is a serious strategical concession -}
11. Qxe2 $16) 11. Be3 $1 {Now the position strongly resembles the 6.Be2
Najdorf. The only difference - the knight's location on the g3- instead of the
b3-square - can be assessed as more useful for White. Moreover, there are
games in which Nb3 has been directed to the f1-square and further either to
the e3- or the g3-ones.} (11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. exd5 Bc8 $13) 11... g6 {A radical
way to stop the jumps of Ng3, both of them with impact on the center.} (11...
Nbd7 {is typically answered with} 12. a4 Rc8 (12... Qa5 13. Qd2 Rfc8 14. Rfd1
$14) 13. a5 $14) 12. Qd2 Re8 ({So is with} 12... Nbd7 13. a4 $14) (12... d5 13.
exd5 Nxd5 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Bf3 $36) 13. Rfe1 $5 $146 ({A improvement upon} 13.
Rfd1 h5 14. h3 Nc6 $13 {the d1-square is left for the other rook.}) 13... h5 ({
Black's opening problems are not over after} 13... d5 14. exd5 Nxd5 15. Bf3
Nxe3 16. Qxe3 Nd7 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bc6 Qb6 (18... Rxb2 $6 19. Rad1 Bc5 20. Qc1
Rb6 21. Bxd7 Bxd7 22. Nge4 $36) 19. Qf3 Qxb2 20. Nd5 Bxd5 21. Bxd5 Nf6 22. Bb3
$14) 14. h3 Nc6 (14... Nbd7 15. a4 $14) 15. Rad1 Rc8 16. a3 $14 *

