dxe5 {An almost obligatory way of recapturing, as witnessed by} (19... Nxe5 $6
20. Qg3 $16) ({or} 19... Bxe5 $6 20. Bf4 $1 $16) 20. Qg4 (20. Qg3 e4 $1 $13 {
is the usual key for initiating counterplay.}) 20... Rfe8 {The most logical
continuation, otherwise Black will find himself in an inferior queenless
endgame after both} (20... e4 21. Nh6+ Kh7 22. Qxe6 fxe6 23. Ng4 $14) ({and} 
20... Ne7 21. Nh6+ Kh7 22. Qxe6 (22. Qh5 g6 23. Qg4 Rd6 $11) 22... fxe6 23. Ng4
$14) 21. Bg5 (21. Be3 e4 $13) 21... e4 (21... Ne7 $6 22. Nh6+ $1 gxh6 23. Qxe6
fxe6 24. Bxf6 $14) 22. Rae1 Ne5 23. Nh6+ Kf8 24. Qxe6 Rxe6 25. Rxe4 ({After
the preliminary} 25. Bxf6 Rxf6 26. Rxf6 gxf6 27. Rxe4 {the obvious} Rd2 {
will regain the pawn and the draw is the most likely outcome.}) 25... Nf3+ $1 (
25... Bxg5 26. Nxf7 Nxf7 27. Rxe6 Rd2 28. Rfe1 $14) 26. gxf3 Bxg5 27. Rxe6 fxe6
28. Ng4 Be7 $1 $44 {[%cal Ge7c5] This subtle retreat is the tactical
justification of Black's small operation - from the c5-square the bishop will
secure the own rook's penetration on the penultimate rank with enough
counterplay.} 29. Kg2 Bc5 30. Kg3 Rd2 31. Ne5 Ke7 $11 *

